DEMO SCRIPT — Traffic Inspection & Mitigation System
=====================================================
Audience: Professor (non-technical)
Duration: ~15–20 minutes


────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
BEFORE THE DEMO
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

1. Start the system (do this a few minutes before she arrives):

   docker-compose up --build -d

2. Open the dashboard in a browser:

   http://localhost:8080

3. You land on the Live Demo page (Page 5 — "Live Demo" tab is active).
   Wait until the top status bar shows:
   - IDMS         → healthy  (green dot)
   - Load Balancer → healthy  (green dot)
   - Servers online → 4 / 4

   If any are red, wait 10–15 seconds and refresh. Docker is still starting.

4. The anomaly baseline builds automatically in the background.
   There is NO warm-up button to click — the system does it on its own.
   You will see the Allow counter slowly climbing on the Live Demo page.
   After ~15 seconds the anomaly engine has enough samples to detect bursts.

5. Make sure all counters read 0. If not, click
   "Reset — Clear All Demo State" to wipe leftover state from a previous run.


────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
WALKTHROUGH STRUCTURE
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

The dashboard has 5 tabs in the navigation bar at the top:

  1 · Load Balancer   2 · Rule Engine   3 · Anomaly Engine
  4 · Mitigation       5 · Live Demo

Walk through pages 1–4 as visual explanations (no live attack needed).
Use page 5 for the live demonstrations.


────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
PAGE 1 — LOAD BALANCER  (click tab "1 · Load Balancer")
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

Say:
  "This is the load balancer. It sits in front of four identical
   backend servers and distributes incoming requests across them
   so no single server gets overwhelmed.

   I'll show you what that looks like."

Action: Click [Start Simulation]

Watch the animated diagram:
  - Requests travel from the Client box to the Load Balancer
  - From there they fan out to the four server boxes in sequence
    (round robin — one after another, evenly)

Say:
  "That's round robin — request 1 goes to Server 1, request 2
   to Server 2, and so on. But there are two other modes."

Action: Click [Source Hashing], then [Least Loaded]

Say:
  "Source hashing always sends the same type of request to the
   same server — useful for caching. Least loaded always picks
   the server with the fewest active requests right now.

   Scroll down to see what we improved for each algorithm."

Point to the Before/After table:
  - Round robin: added background health checks (no per-request HTTP probes),
    thread-safe iterator lock
  - Source hashing: MD5 first-8-chars optimisation, ring fallback on failure
  - Least loaded: removed duplicate load counter, random jitter for tie-breaking


────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
PAGE 2 — RULE ENGINE  (click tab "2 · Rule Engine")
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

Say:
  "The load balancer only decides WHERE to send traffic, not
   WHETHER it should be sent. That's the problem we're solving.

   The first security layer is the Rule Engine. It checks every
   request against six fixed rules — like a bouncer with a list."

Point to the pipeline diagram:
  - Rule Engine box is highlighted; everything else is dimmed
  - "It sits in front of the load balancer — every request passes
    through here first."

Scroll to the rule cards:
  - Explain each briefly: auth check first (API key), then injection
    patterns, then rate limiting, endpoint scanning, payload size

Say:
  "The order matters. An unauthenticated request is rejected
   immediately without even checking if it contains SQL injection —
   that saves processing time."

Point to the request trace:
  - "This shows a SQL injection attempt flowing through the pipeline:
    it passes the auth check, then hits the injection detector and
    gets redirected to the honeypot instead of being blocked."


────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
PAGE 3 — ANOMALY ENGINE  (click tab "3 · Anomaly Engine")
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

Say:
  "The rule engine is fast but it only catches known patterns.
   A smart attacker could spread their flood over a longer time
   period and stay under the rate limit.

   The Anomaly Engine catches that. Instead of a fixed rule, it
   learns what normal traffic looks like for each IP address, then
   flags behaviour that deviates significantly."

Point to the Z-score formula:
  "This is the formula — a Modified Z-score. It measures how
   far each request's arrival time is from the learned average
   for that IP. Once the gap drops far enough below the baseline,
   the system knows something has changed."

Point to the IAT distribution chart:
  "The blue bars are the steady baseline. The orange spike is
   what a burst attack looks like — requests arriving much faster
   than the learned normal."

Check the baseline status indicator:
  "This shows the anomaly engine is already warmed up — it started
   building the baseline automatically when the system booted.
   No manual action needed."


────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
PAGE 4 — MITIGATION  (click tab "4 · Mitigation")
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

Say:
  "The Mitigation Controller is the final decision maker.
   It takes the verdict from the Rule Engine and Anomaly Engine
   and decides exactly what to do."

Point to the decision tree:
  - Block → 403 returned immediately
  - Honeypot → redirected to decoy server
  - Deprioritise → forwarded but tagged
  - Allow → forwarded normally

Say:
  "Notice the middle option — deprioritise. If the system isn't
   sure, it lets the request through but marks it as suspicious.
   If enough suspicious requests come from the same IP within
   two minutes, it automatically escalates to a full block."

Action: Click [Add Strike] repeatedly in the escalation simulator

Watch the progress bar fill to 8 and fire "ESCALATION" at the end.

Say:
  "That's 8 suspicious events — the threshold. The system learned
   on its own that this is not a normal traffic spike."

Point to the persistence section:
  "All of this state is saved to SQLite on disk, not just in memory.
   If the IDMS container restarts, the block history survives."


────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
PAGE 5 — LIVE DEMO  (click tab "5 · Live Demo")
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

Say:
  "Now let me show all of this working in real time. I'll trigger
   each type of attack and you'll see the counters and events
   table update live."

The page auto-refreshes every 2 seconds. Counters should read 0
(or click Reset first).


--- Demo 1: Wrong API Key ---

Say:
  "Every request must include a valid API key. Watch what happens
   when someone sends the wrong one."

Action: Click  [Wrong API Key]

Watch the detections table:
  - A new row appears immediately
  - Outcome: red "Blocked" pill
  - Rule: "Wrong API Key"
  - Block counter: goes up by 1

Say:
  "Caught and rejected before it even reached the load balancer.
   Zero compute wasted on the real servers."

Action: Click  [Reset]


--- Demo 2: SQL Injection ---

Say:
  "SQL injection is when an attacker hides database commands inside
   a normal-looking request. Watch what we do with it."

Action: Click  [SQL Injection]

Watch the detections table:
  - Outcome: orange "Honeypot" pill
  - Rule: "SQL/NoSQL Injection"

Say:
  "It wasn't blocked — it was redirected to a honeypot. That's a
   decoy server. The attacker gets back a fake success response,
   so they think their attack worked and keep sending more. We
   capture everything they send. The real servers never see it."

Action: Click  [Reset]


--- Demo 3: Rate Flood ---

Say:
  "A denial-of-service attack just hammers the system with as many
   requests as possible. I'm going to send 250 requests in under
   three seconds from the same IP."

Action: Click  [Rate Flood (250 req)]

Watch the dashboard:
  - The Allow counter climbs briefly, then the Block counter takes over
  - Request rate chart spikes
  - Events table fills with red "Blocked" rows labelled "Rate Flood"

Say:
  "The rule engine allows up to 200 requests per 10-second window
   per IP. Once that's crossed, the IP is blocked and all further
   requests are rejected immediately."

Action: Click  [Reset]


--- Demo 4: Burst Anomaly ---

Say:
  "This one is subtler. The attacker is using a valid API key,
   sending valid requests — just suddenly sending them much faster
   than they usually do. No fixed rule would catch this.
   The Anomaly Engine will."

Action: Click  [Burst Anomaly]

Watch the detections table:
  - New rows appear with "Burst Anomaly" or "Anomaly" label
  - Outcome: yellow/amber "Deprioritised" pill
  - Rule engine shows clean; anomaly engine fires

Say:
  "The inter-arrival time between requests dropped far below the
   learned baseline for this IP. The system flagged them. If they
   keep coming, that escalates to a full block automatically — the
   same escalation you saw on Page 4."

Action: Click  [Reset]


